===Etymology 2===
{{ja-kanjitab|いもうと|yomi=k}}

{{IPAchar|/imo ɸito/}} → {{IPAchar|/imowito/}} → *{{IPAchar|/imowuto/}} → {{IPAchar|/imoːto/}}

Originally a compound of {{com|ja|sort=いもうと||alt1=妹|tr1=imo|t1=[[sister]], [[close]] [[female]] [[companion]]|人|tr2=hito|t2=[[person]]}}.<ref name="KDJ2"/><ref name="SMK5"/><ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref><ref name="DDJS">{{R:Digital-Daijisen}}</ref>  First cited in ''{{w|The Tales of Ise}}'' of the early 900s.<ref name="KDJ2"/>

This is an instance of {{m|ja|:w:ja:ウ音便|ウ音便|tr=u onbin|''u'' sound shift}}, found in terms with bilabial consonants ({{IPAchar|/m/}}, {{IPAchar|/b/}}, {{IPAchar|/w/}}) followed by ''i''; commonly seen in terms such as {{m|ja|玄人|tr=kurōto||[[professional]]}}, {{m|ja|素人|tr=shirōto||[[amateur]]}}, or possibly, {{m|ja|相撲|tr=sumō||[[sumo]]}}.

